You need to create and annotate a class with `@PropertySource` like this:

    @PropertySource(&quot;${my.config.location}&quot;)
    @Component
    public class Config {
    
        @Value(&quot;${ccr.read.clientSecret}&quot;)
        private String clientSecret;
    
        public String getClientSecret() {
            return clientSecret;
        }
    
        public void setClientSecret(String clientSecret) {
            this.clientSecret = clientSecret;
        }
    
        @Override
        public String toString() {
            return &quot;Config{&quot; +
                    &quot;clientSecret=&#39;&quot; + clientSecret + &#39;\&#39;&#39; +
                    &#39;}&#39;;
        }
    }


You can have `@PropertySource` also on a configuration class.

Now run the application with `-Dmy.config.location=file:D:/myname/Properties/override.properties` variable. Notice that I changed the variable name, for reason described below.

What&#39;s wrong with your approach: `-Dspring.config.location` points to the `application.properties` file location but you already have one in the classpath. By overwriting the `application.properties` file location, you replace the existent one from classpath with `...\override.properties` which is not a directory.

&gt; By default Spring Boot tries to load application.properties (or
&gt; application.yml) from the following locations:
&gt; classpath:/,classpath:/config/,file:./,file:./config/. Of course, we
&gt; may override it. You can change the name of main configuration file by
&gt; setting environment property spring.config.name or just change the
&gt; whole searching path by setting property **spring.config.location**. It
&gt; can contains names of directories, as well as file paths.

See [this post][1] for further details.


  [1]: https://piotrminkowski.wordpress.com/2019/03/11/a-magic-around-spring-boot-externalized-configuration/

